  "prompt": "What are the best romantic comedy movies?",
  "response": "Okay, \"best\" is subjective, as what one person finds hilarious and romantic, another might find cheesy. However, based on popularity, critical acclaim, and lasting impact, here's a list of some of the best romantic comedies, broken down by category to give you a variety to choose from:\n\n**Classics (Influential and Widely Loved):**\n\n*   **When Harry Met Sally... (1989):**  A must-see.  Smart, witty, and asks the timeless question: Can men and women truly be just friends?  Excellent dialogue and performances from Billy Crystal and Meg Ryan.\n*   **Annie Hall (1977):** While arguably more complex than a straight rom-com, it's a brilliant, quirky, and often hilarious exploration of love, relationships, and modern life. Woody Allen at his peak.\n*   **The Princess Bride (1987):**  A fantasy adventure with a strong romantic core and fantastic comedic elements.  Suitable for all ages.  \"As you wish...\"\n*   **Bringing Up Baby (1938):** A screwball comedy masterpiece starring Cary Grant and Katharine Hepburn. Fast-paced, madcap, and utterly delightful.\n*   **Roman Holiday (1953):** Audrey Hepburn and Gregory Peck in a charming story about a princess escaping her royal duties and falling for an American reporter in Rome.  Pure romantic escapism.\n\n**Popular and Enduring (Still Highly Enjoyable Today):**\n\n*   **Sleepless in Seattle (1993):**  A classic meet-cute with a touch of magic.  Meg Ryan and Tom Hanks have great chemistry, and the story is undeniably romantic.\n*   **Pretty Woman (1990):**  A modern fairy tale with Julia Roberts and Richard Gere.  A bit of a controversial premise now, but still a crowd-pleaser.\n*   **You've Got Mail (1998):** Another Meg Ryan/Tom Hanks collaboration, this time about falling in love anonymously online.  A sweet and charming story set in the pre-social media era.\n*   **Notting Hill (1999):**  Hugh Grant at his charming best, alongside Julia Roberts as a famous actress who falls for an ordinary bookseller.\n*   **10 Things I Hate About You (1999):** A clever and witty adaptation of Shakespeare's *The Taming of the Shrew*, with a great cast and a fantastic soundtrack.\n*   **Bridget Jones's Diary (2001):**  Hilarious and relatable, with Ren\u00e9e Zellweger perfectly capturing the anxieties and foibles of a modern single woman.\n*   **Love Actually (2003):**  An ensemble cast tells multiple interwoven love stories during the Christmas season.  Sentimental and feel-good.\n\n**Modern Rom-Coms (2000s and Beyond):**\n\n*   **500 Days of Summer (2009):** A deconstruction of the romantic comedy genre, told from the male perspective.  Stylish, funny, and bittersweet.\n*   **Crazy Stupid Love (2011):**  A smart and funny ensemble comedy about love, relationships, and growing up.  Steve Carell, Ryan Gosling, Emma Stone, and Julianne Moore are all excellent.\n*   **Silver Linings Playbook (2012):**  Deals with serious issues (mental health) but is also funny, heartwarming, and features strong performances from Bradley Cooper and Jennifer Lawrence.\n*   **Trainwreck (2015):**  Amy Schumer's raunchy and hilarious take on modern relationships.\n*   **The Big Sick (2017):** Based on a true story, this is a funny, heartwarming, and insightful look at love, family, and cultural differences.\n*   **Set It Up (2018):**  A clever and charming Netflix original about two assistants who try to set up their demanding bosses.  A refreshing take on the genre.\n*   **Long Shot (2019):** A surprisingly sweet and funny movie about an unlikely couple: a presidential candidate (Charlize Theron) and her childhood friend (Seth Rogen), a journalist.\n*   **Palm Springs (2020):** A sci-fi rom-com about two strangers who get stuck in a time loop.  Hilarious, inventive, and surprisingly poignant.\n*  **Anyone But You (2023):** A more recent entry starring Sydney Sweeney and Glen Powell that has taken the rom-com world by storm.\n\n**Indie and Quirky:**\n\n*   **Am\u00e9lie (2001):**  A visually stunning and whimsical French film about a young woman who decides to spread joy and find love in Paris.\n*   **Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind (2004):**  A mind-bending and emotional film about a couple who erase each other from their memories.  More complex than a traditional rom-com, but profoundly moving.\n*   **Juno (2007):**  A sharp and witty coming-of-age story about a pregnant teenager.  Funny, heartfelt, and surprisingly mature.\n*   **Ruby Sparks (2012):** A novelist creates his dream girl, only to have her magically come to life. Explores the pitfalls of idealizing a partner.\n\n**LGBTQ+ Rom-Coms:**\n\n*   **But I'm a Cheerleader (1999):** A satire on gender roles. A cheerleader is sent to a conversion camp when her parents suspect she is a lesbian.\n*   **Love, Simon (2018):** A sweet and heartwarming coming-of-age story about a gay teenager who is struggling to come out.\n*   **Happiest Season (2020):**  A holiday rom-com about a woman who is planning to propose to her girlfriend, only to discover that she is not out to her family.\n*   **Bros (2022):** A mainstream, big-budget gay rom-com that follows two men with commitment issues as they attempt a relationship.\n\n**To help me narrow down recommendations further, tell me:**\n\n*   **What are some movies you've enjoyed in the past?**\n*   **What kind of humor do you prefer (e.g., slapstick, witty, dry, sarcastic)?**\n*   **Are you looking for something light and fluffy, or something with more depth?**\n*   **Are there any actors or actresses you particularly like?**\n\nEnjoy the movies! Let me know if you want more suggestions.\n",
